# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: iec-62443-security
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:iec-62443-security/cyber-physical-system] CPS involves transdisciplinary approaches, merging theory of cybernetics, mechatronics, design and process science.
[src:iec-62443-security/cyber-physical-system] The process control is often referred to as embedded systems.
[src:iec-62443-security/cyber-physical-system] In embedded systems, the emphasis tends to be more on the computational elements, and less on an intense link between the computational and physical elements.
[src:iec-62443-security/cyber-physical-system] CPS is also similar to the Internet of Things (IoT), sharing the same basic architecture; nevertheless, CPS presents a higher combination and coordination between physical and computational elements.
[src:iec-62443-security/cyber-physical-system] Examples of CPS include smart grid, autonomous automobile systems, medical monitoring, industrial control systems, robotics systems, recycling and automatic pilot avionics.
[src:iec-62443-security/cyber-physical-system] Precursors of cyber-physical systems can be found in areas as diverse as aerospace, automotive, chemical processes, civil infrastructure, energy, healthcare, manufacturing, transportation, entertainment, and consumer appliances.
[src:iec-62443-security/cyber-physical-system] Unlike more traditional embedded systems, a full-fledged CPS is typically designed as a network of interacting elements with physical input and output instead of as standalone devices.
[src:iec-62443-security/cyber-physical-system] The notion is closely tied to concepts of robotics and sensor networks with intelligence mechanisms proper of computational intelligence leading the pathway.
[src:iec-62443-security/cyber-physical-system] Ongoing advances in science and engineering improve the link between computational and physical elements by means of intelligent mechanisms, increasing the adaptability, autonomy, efficiency, functionality, reliability, safety, and usability of cyber-physical systems.
[src:iec-62443-security/cyber-physical-system] Mobile cyber-physical systems, in which the physical system under study has inherent mobility, are a prominent subcategory of cyber-physical systems.
[src:iec-62443-security/cyber-physical-system] Examples of mobile physical systems include mobile robotics and electronics transported by humans or animals.
[src:iec-62443-security/cyber-physical-system] The rise in popularity of smartphones has increased interest in the area of mobile cyber-physical systems.
[src:iec-62443-security/cyber-physical-system] Examples of mobile cyber-physical systems include applications to track and analyze CO2 emissions, detect traffic accidents, insurance telematics and provide situational awareness services to first responders, measure traffic, and monitor cardiac patients.
[src:iec-62443-security/cyber-physical-system] Common applications of CPS typically fall under sensor-based communication-enabled autonomous systems.
[src:iec-62443-security/cyber-physical-system] For example, many wireless sensor networks monitor some aspect of the environment and relay the processed information to a central node.
[src:iec-62443-security/cyber-physical-system] Other types of CPS include smart grid, autonomous automotive systems, medical monitoring, process control systems, distributed robotics, recycling and automatic pilot avionics.
[src:iec-62443-security/cyber-physical-system] A real-world example of such a system is the Distributed Robot Garden at MIT in which a team of robots tend a garden of tomato plants.
[src:iec-62443-security/cyber-physical-system] This system combines distributed sensing (each plant is equipped with a sensor node monitoring its status), navigation, manipulation and wireless networking.
[src:iec-62443-security/cyber-physical-system] A focus on the control system aspects of CPS that pervade critical infrastructure can be found in the efforts of the Idaho National Laboratory and collaborators researching resilient control systems.
[src:iec-62443-security/cyber-physical-system] This effort takes a holistic approach to next generation design, and considers the resilience aspects that are not well quantified, such as cyber security, human interaction and complex interdependencies.
[src:iec-62443-security/cyber-physical-system] Another example is MIT's ongoing CarTel project where a fleet of taxis work by collecting real-time traffic information in the Boston area.
[src:iec-62443-security/cyber-physical-system] Together with historical data, this information is then used for calculating fastest routes for a given time of the day.
[src:iec-62443-security/cyber-physical-system] CPS are also used in electric grids to perform advanced control, especially in the smart grids context to enhance the integration of distributed renewable generation.The Special remedial action scheme are needed to limit the current flows in the grid when wind farm generation is too high.
[src:iec-62443-security/cyber-physical-system] In industry the cyber-physical systems empowered by Cloud technologies have led to novel approaches that paved the path to Industry 4.0 as the European Commission IMC-AESOP project with partners such as Schneider Electric, SAP, Honeywell, Microsoft etc. demonstrated.
[src:iec-62443-security/cyber-physical-system] In the area of digital agriculture (alternately precision agriculture), CPS technologies are used for measurement of soil quality and moisture content and determining the right level of irrigation or fertilizer or pesticide usage.
[src:iec-62443-security/cyber-physical-system] A challenge in the development of embedded and cyber-physical systems is the large differences in the design practice between the various engineering disciplines involved, such as software and mechanical engineering.
[src:iec-62443-security/cyber-physical-system] Additionally, as of today there is no "language" in terms of design practice that is common to all the involved disciplines in CPS.
[src:iec-62443-security/cyber-physical-system] Today, in a marketplace where rapid innovation is assumed to be essential, engineers from all disciplines need to be able to explore system designs collaboratively, allocating responsibilities to software and physical elements, and analyzing trade-offs between them.
[src:iec-62443-security/cyber-physical-system] Recent advances show that coupling disciplines by using co-simulation will allow disciplines to cooperate without enforcing new tools or design methods.
[src:iec-62443-security/cyber-physical-system] Results from the MODELISAR project show that this approach is viable by proposing a new standard for co-simulation in the form of the Functional Mock-up Interface.
[src:iec-62443-security/cyber-physical-system] The US National Science Foundation (NSF) has identified cyber-physical systems as a key area of research.
[src:iec-62443-security/cyber-physical-system] Through its CPS Program, it awards "Frontier" projects that are large-scale projects ($5-7M each) meant to significantly move the CPS technology forward.
[src:iec-62443-security/cyber-physical-system] Starting in late 2006, the NSF and other United States federal agencies sponsored several workshops on cyber-physical systems.
[src:iec-62443-security/defense-in-depth-computing] The idea behind the defense in depth approach is to defend a system against any particular attack using several independent methods.
[src:iec-62443-security/defense-in-depth-computing] It is a layering tactic, conceived by the National Security Agency (NSA) as a comprehensive approach to information and electronic security.
[src:iec-62443-security/defense-in-depth-computing] Defense in depth is sometimes thought of as forming the layers of an onion, with data at the core of the onion, people the next outer layer of the onion, and network security, host-based security, and application security forming the outermost layers of the onion.
[src:iec-62443-security/defense-in-depth-computing] Defense in depth can be divided into three overarching areas: Physical, Technical, and Administrative.
[src:iec-62443-security/defense-in-depth-computing] Physical controls are anything that physically limits or prevents access to IT systems.
[src:iec-62443-security/defense-in-depth-computing] Examples of physical defensive security are: fences, guards, dogs, and CCTV systems.
[src:iec-62443-security/defense-in-depth-computing] Technical controls are hardware or software whose purpose is to protect systems and resources.
[src:iec-62443-security/defense-in-depth-computing] Examples of technical controls include disk encryption, file integrity software, authentication, network security controls, antiviruses, and behavioural analysis software.
[src:iec-62443-security/defense-in-depth-computing] In the event that one layer of defence fails, defense in depth aims to ensure network security via a second-line of defence.
[src:iec-62443-security/defense-in-depth-computing] For example, if an attacker penetrates a computer system at a given OSI layer (e.g.
[src:iec-62443-security/defense-in-depth-computing] Layer 3), a redundancy should exist at another layer (Layer 7) to ensure layered defense.
[src:iec-62443-security/defense-in-depth-computing] Administrative controls are the organization's policies and procedures and govern the organisation's human resources, technology, and operations.
[src:iec-62443-security/iec-62443] In 2002, the International Society of Automation (ISA), a professional automation engineering society and ANSI-accredited standards development organization (SDO) established a standards committee (ISA99).
[src:iec-62443-security/iec-62443] This committee developed a multi-part series of standards and technical reports addressing the cybersecurity of Automation and Control Systems.
[src:iec-62443-security/iec-62443] These standards were initially published as *ANSI/ISA-99* or *ISA99* standards.
[src:iec-62443-security/iec-62443] Around 2010, ISA99 strengthened its relationship with the International Electrotechnical Commission (IEC), leading to the renaming of the standards to *ANSI/ISA-62443*.
[src:iec-62443-security/iec-62443] The available content was submitted to and used by IEC working groups.
[src:iec-62443-security/iec-62443] Since then, the series has been commonly referred to as IEC 62443.
[src:iec-62443-security/iec-62443] Meanwhile, the German engineering associations VDI and VDE released the *VDI/VDE 2182* guidelines in 2011.
[src:iec-62443-security/iec-62443] The guidelines describe how to handle information security in industrial automation environments and were also submitted to and used by the IEC working groups.
[src:iec-62443-security/iec-62443] The IEC 62443 series of standards is maintained by the International Electrotechnical Commission (IEC) Technical Committee 65 Working Group 10 (IEC TC65 WG10).
[src:iec-62443-security/iec-62443] The IEC working group and ISA99 committee continue to collaborate, creating joint leadership and project teams to develop the standards in the IEC 62443 series.
[src:iec-62443-security/iec-62443] Their collaboration integrates the processes and procedures of both ISA and IEC Directives, ensuring alignment in the development process.
[src:iec-62443-security/iec-62443] The resulting standards are published by ISA as ANSI/ISA 62443 in the United States and by IEC as IEC 62443 internationally.
[src:iec-62443-security/iec-62443] For any given part of the series, the technical content of the ISA and IEC editions is identical where both organizations have accepted the content.
[src:iec-62443-security/iec-62443] The relationship between IEC and ISA in the development of the IEC 62443 series is characterized by complementary roles.
[src:iec-62443-security/iec-62443] IEC serves as the global standardization body responsible for publishing and maintaining the IEC 62443 series, while ISA contributes significant technical expertise, industry insight, and foundational drafts through its ISA99 committee.
[src:iec-62443-security/iec-62443] ISA primarily focuses on the U.S. market and publishes standards under the ANSI/ISA 62443 designation.
[src:iec-62443-security/iec-62443] IEC, on the other hand, ensures global adoption and harmonization of the standards as IEC 62443.
[src:iec-62443-security/iec-62443] While both organizations collaborate on the majority of standards, they retain the independence to develop and publish standards separately when consensus cannot be reached.
[src:iec-62443-security/iec-62443] For example, IEC developed and published IEC 62443-6-1 independently without ISA involvement.
[src:iec-62443-security/iec-62443] The IEC has approved the IEC 62443 family of standards as 'horizontal standards'.
[src:iec-62443-security/iec-62443] This means that when sector specific standards for operational technology are being developed by subject matter experts, the IEC 62443 standards must be used at the foundation for requirements addressing security in those standards.
[src:iec-62443-security/iec-62443] This approach serves to avoid the proliferation of partial and/or conflicting requirements for addressing security of automation and control systems across industry sectors where the same or similar technology or products are deployed at operating sites.
[src:iec-62443-security/iec-62443] Policies and Procedures: This primarily describes a system for managing industrial IT security.
[src:iec-62443-security/iec-62443] System: Various specifications for security functions of control and automation systems are described here.
[src:iec-62443-security/iec-62443] Components and Requirements: The requirements for product development processes for components of an automation solution are described here.
[src:iec-62443-security/iec-62443] Profiles:This section is intended to define industry-specific cybersecurity requirements and provide a structured approach to implementing measures based on the cybersecurity profiles described in IEC 62443-1-5.
[src:iec-62443-security/iec-62443] Evaluation: This section describes assessment methodologies that ensure that assessment results are consistent and reproducible with regard to the requirements of the individual parts.
[src:iec-62443-security/iec-62443] The following table lists the parts of the IEC 62443 series of standards published to date with their status and title.
[src:iec-62443-security/iec-62443] The standards in the IEC 62443 series of standards evolve constantly.
[src:iec-62443-security/iec-62443] There are several concepts that form the foundation of the IEC 62443 series.
[src:iec-62443-security/iec-62443] The different roles each follow a risk-based approach to prevent and manage security risks in their activities.
[src:iec-62443-security/iec-62443] The standards describe different maturity levels for processes through so-called "maturity levels".
[src:iec-62443-security/iec-62443] To fulfill a certain level of a maturity level, all process-related requirements must always be practiced during product development or integration, i.e. the selection of only individual criteria ("cherry picking") is not standard-compliant.
[src:iec-62443-security/iec-62443] Technical requirements for systems (IEC 62443-3-3) and products (IEC 62443-4-2) are evaluated in the standard by four so-called Security Levels (SL).
[src:iec-62443-security/iec-62443] The different levels indicate the resistance against different classes of attackers.
[src:iec-62443-security/iec-62443] The standard emphasizes that the levels should be evaluated per technical requirement (see IEC 62443-1-1) and are not suitable for the general classification of products.
[src:iec-62443-security/iec-62443] Application of this concept involves grouping the systems and components of the automation and control system into a set of zones and conduits.
[src:iec-62443-security/iec-62443] Zones divide a system into homogeneous zones by grouping the (logical or physical) assets with common security requirements.
[src:iec-62443-security/iec-62443] The security requirements are defined by Security Level (SL).
[src:iec-62443-security/iec-62443] The level required for a zone is determined by the risk analysis.
[src:iec-62443-security/iec-62443] Zones have boundaries that separate the elements inside the zone from those outside.
[src:iec-62443-security/iec-62443] Information moves within and between zones.
[src:iec-62443-security/iec-62443] Zones can be divided into sub-zones that define different security levels (Security Level) and thus enable defense-in-depth.
[src:iec-62443-security/iec-62443] Conduits group the elements that allow communication between two zones.
[src:iec-62443-security/iec-62443] They provide security functions that enable secure communication and allow the coexistence of zones with different security levels.
[src:iec-62443-security/iec-62443] Processes, systems and products used in automation and control environments can be certified as conforming to IEC 62443.
[src:iec-62443-security/iec-62443] Many testing, inspection, and certification (TIC) companies offer product and process certifications based on IEC 62443.
[src:iec-62443-security/iec-62443] By accrediting according to the ISO/IEC 17000 series of standards, the companies share a single, consistent set of requirements for IEC 62443 certifications which elevates the usefulness of the resulting certificates of conformance.
[src:iec-62443-security/iec-62443] IEC 62443 certification schemes have been established by several global testing, inspection, and certification (TIC) companies.
[src:iec-62443-security/iec-62443] The schemes are based on the referenced standards and define test methods, surveillance audit policies, public documentation policies, and other specific aspects of their program.
[src:iec-62443-security/iec-62443] Security certification programs for IEC 62443 standards are being offered globally by many recognized Certification Bodies (CB), including Bureau Veritas, Intertek, SGS-TÜV Saar, TÜV Nord, TÜV Rheinland, TÜV SÜD and UL.
[src:iec-62443-security/iec-62443] A global infrastructure of national accreditation bodies (AB) ensures consistent evaluation of the IEC 62443.
[src:iec-62443-security/iec-62443] The ABs operate per the requirements of ISO/IEC 17011, a standard that contains requirements for the competence, consistency, and impartiality of accreditation bodies when accrediting conformity assessment bodies.
[src:iec-62443-security/iec-62443] ABs are members of the IAF for work in management systems, products, services, and personnel accreditation or the ILAC for laboratory accreditation.
[src:iec-62443-security/iec-62443] A Multilateral Recognition Arrangement (MLA) between ABs will ensure global recognition of accredited CBs.
[src:iec-62443-security/iec-62443] TIC companies are accredited by an AB to provide inspection according to the ISO/IEC 17020, testing laboratories according to ISO/IEC 17025 and certification of products, processes, and services according to ISO/IEC 17065.
[src:iec-62443-security/iec-62443] The IEC System for Conformity Assessment Schemes for Electrotechnical Equipment and Components (IECEE) Certification Body Scheme (CB Scheme) is a multilateral agreement that facilitates market access for manufacturers of electrical and electronic products.
[src:iec-62443-security/iec-62443] Under the CB Scheme processes, products and systems can be certified according to IEC 62443.
[src:iec-62443-security/iec-62443] The origin of the CB Scheme comes from the CEE (former European "Commission for Conformity Testing of Electrical Equipment") and was integrated into the IEC in 1985.
[src:iec-62443-security/iec-62443] Currently, 54 Member Bodies are in the IECEE, 88 NCBs (National Certification Bodies), and 534 CB Test Laboratories (CBTL).
[src:iec-62443-security/iec-62443] In the field of product certification, this procedure is used to reduce the complexity in the approval procedure for manufacturers of products tested and certified according to harmonized standards.
[src:iec-62443-security/iec-62443] A product that has been tested by a CBTL (certified testing laboratory) according to a harmonized standard such as the IEC 62443, can use the CB report as a basis for a later national certification and approval such as GS, PSE, CCC, NOM, GOST/R, BSMI.
[src:iec-62443-security/iec-62443] The ISA Security Compliance Institute (ISCI), a wholly owned subsidiary of the ISA, created an industry consensus conformity assessment scheme that certifies to the IEC 62443 standards and operates under the ISASecure brand.
[src:iec-62443-security/iec-62443] This scheme is used to certify automation control systems, components and processes.
[src:iec-62443-security/iec-62443] ISASecure certifications were expanded to include the Industrial IOT component certification (ICSA) in December 2022.
[src:iec-62443-security/iec-62443] Certification Bodies in the ISASecure certification scheme are independently accredited by ISO 17011 Accreditation Bodies to the ISASecure technical readiness requirements and the ISO 17025 and ISO 17065 standards.
[src:iec-62443-security/iec-62443] Multilateral recognition agreements under the IAF ensure that the ISASecure certifications are mutually recognized by all global IAF signatories.
[src:iec-62443-security/industrial-control-system] An **industrial control system** (**ICS**) is an electronic control system and associated instrumentation used for industrial process control.
[src:iec-62443-security/industrial-control-system] Control systems can range in size from a few modular panel-mounted controllers to large interconnected and interactive distributed control systems (DCSs) with many thousands of field connections.
[src:iec-62443-security/industrial-control-system] Control systems receive data from remote sensors measuring process variables (PVs), compare the collected data with desired setpoints (SPs), and derive command functions that are used to control a process through the final control elements (FCEs), such as control valves.
[src:iec-62443-security/industrial-control-system] Larger systems are usually implemented by supervisory control and data acquisition (SCADA) systems, or DCSs, and programmable logic controllers (PLCs), though SCADA and PLC systems are scalable down to small systems with few control loops.
[src:iec-62443-security/industrial-control-system] Such systems are extensively used in industries such as chemical processing, pulp and paper manufacture, power generation, oil and gas processing, and telecommunications.
[src:iec-62443-security/industrial-control-system] The simplest control systems are based around small discrete controllers with a single control loop each.
[src:iec-62443-security/industrial-control-system] These are usually panel mounted, which allows direct viewing of the front panel and provides a means of manual intervention by the operator, either to manually control the process or to change control setpoints.
[src:iec-62443-security/industrial-control-system] Originally, these would be pneumatic controllers, a few of which are still in use, but nearly all are now electronic.
[src:iec-62443-security/industrial-control-system] Quite complex systems can be created with networks of these controllers communicating using industry-standard protocols.
[src:iec-62443-security/industrial-control-system] Networking allows the use of local or remote SCADA operator interfaces and enables the cascading and interlocking of controllers.
[src:iec-62443-security/industrial-control-system] However, as the number of control loops increases for a system design, there is a point where the use of a programmable logic controller (PLC) or distributed control system (DCS) is more manageable or cost-effective.
[src:iec-62443-security/industrial-control-system] A distributed control system (DCS) is a digital process control system (PCS) for a process or plant, wherein controller functions and field connection modules are distributed throughout the system.
[src:iec-62443-security/industrial-control-system] As the number of control loops grows, DCS becomes more cost effective than discrete controllers.
[src:iec-62443-security/industrial-control-system] Additionally, a DCS provides supervisory viewing and management over large industrial processes.
[src:iec-62443-security/industrial-control-system] In a DCS, a hierarchy of controllers is connected by communication networks, allowing centralized control rooms and local on-plant monitoring and control.
[src:iec-62443-security/industrial-control-system] A DCS enables easy configuration of plant controls such as cascaded loops and interlocks, and easy interfacing with other computer systems such as production control.
[src:iec-62443-security/industrial-control-system] It also enables more sophisticated alarm handling, introduces automatic event logging, removes the need for physical records such as chart recorders and allows the control equipment to be networked and thereby located locally to the equipment being controlled to reduce cabling.
[src:iec-62443-security/industrial-control-system] A DCS typically uses custom-designed processors as controllers and uses either proprietary interconnections or standard protocols for communication.
[src:iec-62443-security/industrial-control-system] Input and output modules form the peripheral components of the system.
[src:iec-62443-security/industrial-control-system] The processors receive information from input modules, process the information and decide control actions to be performed by the output modules.
[src:iec-62443-security/industrial-control-system] The input modules receive information from sensing instruments in the process (or field) and the output modules transmit instructions to the final control elements, such as control valves.
[src:iec-62443-security/industrial-control-system] The field inputs and outputs can either be continuously changing analog signals, e.g., current loop or 2-state signals that switch either *on* or *off*, such as relay contacts or a semiconductor switch.
[src:iec-62443-security/industrial-control-system] Distributed control systems can normally also support Foundation Fieldbus, PROFIBUS, HART, Modbus and other digital communication buses that carry not only input and output signals but also advanced messages such as error diagnostics and status signals.
[src:iec-62443-security/industrial-control-system] Supervisory control and data acquisition (SCADA) is a control system architecture that uses computers, networked data communications and graphical user interfaces for high-level process supervisory management.
[src:iec-62443-security/industrial-control-system] The operator interfaces, which enable monitoring and the issuing of process commands, such as controller setpoint changes, are handled through the SCADA supervisory computer system.
[src:iec-62443-security/industrial-control-system] However, the real-time control logic or controller calculations are performed by networked modules which connect to other peripheral devices such as programmable logic controllers and discrete PID controllers which interface to the process plant or machinery.
[src:iec-62443-security/industrial-control-system] The SCADA concept was developed as a universal means of remote access to a variety of local control modules, which could be from different manufacturers, allowing access through standard automation protocols.
[src:iec-62443-security/industrial-control-system] In practice, large SCADA systems have grown to become very similar to distributed control systems in function, but using multiple means of interfacing with the plant.
[src:iec-62443-security/industrial-control-system] They can control large-scale processes that can include multiple sites and work over large distances.
[src:iec-62443-security/industrial-control-system] This is a commonly used architecture industrial control systems, however there are concerns about SCADA systems being vulnerable to cyberwarfare or cyberterrorism attacks.
[src:iec-62443-security/industrial-control-system] The SCADA software operates on a supervisory level as control actions are performed automatically by RTUs or PLCs.
[src:iec-62443-security/industrial-control-system] SCADA control functions are usually restricted to basic overriding or supervisory level intervention.
[src:iec-62443-security/industrial-control-system] A feedback control loop is directly controlled by the RTU or PLC, but the SCADA software monitors the overall performance of the loop.
[src:iec-62443-security/industrial-control-system] For example, a PLC may control the flow of cooling water through part of an industrial process to a set point level, but the SCADA system software will allow operators to change the set points for the flow.
[src:iec-62443-security/industrial-control-system] The SCADA also enables alarm conditions, such as loss of flow or high temperature, to be displayed and recorded.
[src:iec-62443-security/industrial-control-system] PLCs can range from small modular devices with tens of inputs and outputs (I/O) in a housing integral with the processor, to large rack-mounted modular devices with a count of thousands of I/O, and which are often networked to other PLC and SCADA systems.
[src:iec-62443-security/industrial-control-system] They can be designed for multiple arrangements of digital and analog inputs and outputs, extended temperature ranges, immunity to electrical noise, and resistance to vibration and impact.
[src:iec-62443-security/industrial-control-system] Programs to control machine operation are typically stored in battery-backed-up or non-volatile memory.
[src:iec-62443-security/industrial-control-system] Process control of large industrial plants has evolved through many stages.
[src:iec-62443-security/industrial-control-system] Initially, control was from panels local to the process plant.
[src:iec-62443-security/industrial-control-system] However, this required personnel to attend to these dispersed panels, and there was no overall view of the process.
[src:iec-62443-security/industrial-control-system] The next logical development was the transmission of all plant measurements to a permanently staffed central control room.
[src:iec-62443-security/industrial-control-system] Often, the controllers were behind the control room panels, and all automatic and manual control outputs were individually transmitted back to the plant in the form of pneumatic or electrical signals.
[src:iec-62443-security/industrial-control-system] Effectively, this was the centralisation of all the localised panels, with the advantages of reduced manpower requirements and a consolidated overview of the process.
[src:iec-62443-security/industrial-control-system] However, whilst providing a central control focus, this arrangement was inflexible as each control loop had its own controller hardware, so system changes required reconfiguration of signals by re-piping or re-wiring.
[src:iec-62443-security/industrial-control-system] It also required continual operator movement within a large control room in order to monitor the whole process.
[src:iec-62443-security/industrial-control-system] With the coming of electronic processors, high-speed electronic signalling networks and electronic graphic displays, it became possible to replace these discrete controllers with computer-based algorithms, hosted on a network of input/output racks with their own control processors.
[src:iec-62443-security/industrial-control-system] These could be distributed around the plant and would communicate with the graphic displays in the control room.
[src:iec-62443-security/industrial-control-system] The concept of *distributed control* was realised.
[src:iec-62443-security/industrial-control-system] The introduction of distributed control allowed flexible interconnection and re-configuration of plant controls such as cascaded loops and interlocks, and interfacing with other production computer systems.
[src:iec-62443-security/industrial-control-system] For large control systems, the general commercial name *distributed control system* (DCS) was coined to refer to proprietary modular systems from many manufacturers that integrated high-speed networking and a full suite of displays and control racks.
[src:iec-62443-security/industrial-control-system] While the DCS was tailored to meet the needs of large continuous industrial processes, in industries where combinatorial and sequential logic was the primary requirement, the PLC evolved out of a need to replace racks of relays and timers used for event-driven control.
[src:iec-62443-security/industrial-control-system] The old controls were difficult to reconfigure and debug, and PLC control enabled networking of signals to a central control area with electronic displays.
[src:iec-62443-security/industrial-control-system] PLCs were first developed for the automotive industry on vehicle production lines, where sequential logic was becoming very complex.
[src:iec-62443-security/industrial-control-system] It was soon adopted in a large number of other event-driven applications as varied as printing presses and water treatment plants.
[src:iec-62443-security/industrial-control-system] SCADA's history is rooted in distribution applications, such as power, natural gas, and water pipelines, where there is a need to gather remote data through potentially unreliable or intermittent low-bandwidth and high-latency links.
[src:iec-62443-security/industrial-control-system] SCADA systems use open-loop control with sites that are widely separated geographically.
[src:iec-62443-security/industrial-control-system] A SCADA system uses remote terminal units (RTUs) to send supervisory data back to a control centre.
[src:iec-62443-security/industrial-control-system] Most RTU systems always had some capacity to handle local control while the master station is not available.
[src:iec-62443-security/industrial-control-system] However, over the years, RTU systems have grown more and more capable of handling local control.
[src:iec-62443-security/industrial-control-system] The boundaries between DCS and SCADA/PLC systems are blurring as time goes on.
[src:iec-62443-security/industrial-control-system] The technical limits that drove the designs of these various systems are no longer as much of an issue.
[src:iec-62443-security/industrial-control-system] Many PLC platforms can now perform quite well as a small DCS, using remote I/O and are sufficiently reliable that some SCADA systems actually manage closed-loop control over long distances.
[src:iec-62443-security/industrial-control-system] With the increasing speed of today's processors, many DCS products have a full line of PLC-like subsystems that weren't offered when they were initially developed.
[src:iec-62443-security/industrial-control-system] In 1993, with the release of IEC-1131, later to become IEC-61131-3, the industry moved towards increased code standardization with reusable, hardware-independent control software.
[src:iec-62443-security/industrial-control-system] For the first time, object-oriented programming (OOP) became possible within industrial control systems.
[src:iec-62443-security/industrial-control-system] This led to the development of both programmable automation controllers (PAC) and industrial PCs (IPC).
[src:iec-62443-security/industrial-control-system] These are platforms programmed in the five standardized IEC languages: ladder logic, structured text, function block, instruction list and sequential function chart.
[src:iec-62443-security/industrial-control-system] They can also be programmed in modern high-level languages such as C or C++.
[src:iec-62443-security/industrial-control-system] Additionally, they accept models developed in analytical tools such as MATLAB and Simulink.
[src:iec-62443-security/industrial-control-system] Unlike traditional PLCs, which use proprietary operating systems, IPCs utilize Windows IoT.
[src:iec-62443-security/industrial-control-system] IPCs have the advantage of powerful multi-core processors with much lower hardware costs than traditional PLCs and fit well into multiple form factors such as DIN rail mount, combined with a touch-screen as a panel PC, or as an embedded PC.
[src:iec-62443-security/industrial-control-system] New hardware platforms and technology have contributed significantly to the evolution of DCS and SCADA systems, further blurring the boundaries and changing definitions.
[src:iec-62443-security/industrial-control-system] SCADA and PLCs are vulnerable to cyber attack.
[src:iec-62443-security/industrial-control-system] Government Joint Capability Technology Demonstration (JCTD) known as MOSAICS (More Situational Awareness for Industrial Control Systems) is the initial demonstration of cybersecurity defensive capability for critical infrastructure control systems.
[src:iec-62443-security/industrial-control-system] MOSAICS addresses the Department of Defense (DOD) operational need for cyber defense capabilities to defend critical infrastructure control systems from cyber attack, such as power, water and wastewater, and safety controls, affect the physical environment.
[src:iec-62443-security/industrial-control-system] The MOSAICS JCTD prototype will be shared with commercial industry through Industry Days for further research and development, an approach intended to lead to an innovative, game-changing capabilities for cybersecurity for critical infrastructure control systems.
[src:iec-62443-security/operational-technology] The built environment, whether commercial or domestic, is increasingly controlled and monitored via Internet of Things (IoT) and Industrial Internet of Things (IIoT) devices.
[src:iec-62443-security/operational-technology] In this application space, these IoT devices are both interconnected via converged technology edge IoT platforms and or via "cloud" based applications.
[src:iec-62443-security/operational-technology] Embedded Systems are also included in the sphere of operational technology (e.g. smart instrumentation), along with a large subset of scientific data acquisition, control, and computing devices.
[src:iec-62443-security/operational-technology] Systems that process operational data (including electronic, telecommunications, computer systems and technical components) are included under the term operational technology.
[src:iec-62443-security/operational-technology] OT systems can be required to control valves, engines, conveyors and other machines to regulate various process values, such as temperature, pressure, flow, and to monitor them to prevent hazardous conditions.
[src:iec-62443-security/operational-technology] OT systems use various technologies for hardware design and communications protocols, that are unknown in IT.
[src:iec-62443-security/operational-technology] Common problems include supporting legacy systems & devices and numerous vendor architectures and standards.
[src:iec-62443-security/operational-technology] Since OT systems often supervise industrial processes, most of the time availability must be sustained.
[src:iec-62443-security/operational-technology] This often means that real time (or near-real time) processing is required, with high rates of reliability and availability.
[src:iec-62443-security/operational-technology] This kind of environment may also be referred to as industrial information technology (IIT).
[src:iec-62443-security/operational-technology] Historical OT networks utilized proprietary protocols optimized for the required functions, some of which have become adopted as 'standard' industrial communications protocols (e.g.
[src:iec-62443-security/operational-technology] DNP3, Modbus, Profibus, LonWorks, DALI, BACnet, KNX, EnOcean and OPC-UA).
[src:iec-62443-security/operational-technology] More recently IT-standard network protocols are being implemented in OT devices and systems to reduce complexity and increase compatibility with more traditional IT hardware (e.g.
[src:iec-62443-security/operational-technology] TCP/IP); this however has had a demonstrable reduction in security for OT systems, which in the past have relied on air gaps and the inability to run PC-based malware (see Stuxnet for a well-known example of this change).
[src:iec-62443-security/operational-technology] The term operational technology as applied to industrial control systems was first published in a research paper from Gartner in May 2006 (Steenstrup, Sumic, Spiers, Williams) and presented publicly in September 2006 at the Gartner Energy and Utilities IT Summit.
[src:iec-62443-security/operational-technology] Initially the term was applied to power utility control systems, but over time was adopted by other industrial sectors and used in combination with IoT.
[src:iec-62443-security/operational-technology] A principal driver of the adoption of the term was that the nature of operational technology platforms had evolved from bespoke proprietary systems to complex software portfolios that rely on IT infrastructure.
[src:iec-62443-security/operational-technology] This change was termed IT OT convergence.
[src:iec-62443-security/operational-technology] The concept of aligning and integrating the IT and OT systems of industrial companies gained importance as companies realized that physical assets and infrastructure was both managed by OT systems but also generated data for the IT systems running the business.
[src:iec-62443-security/operational-technology] Industrial technology companies such as GE, Hitachi, Honeywell, Siemens, ABB and Rockwell are the main providers of OT platforms and systems either embedded in equipment or added to them for control, management and monitoring.
[src:iec-62443-security/operational-technology] These industrial technology companies have needed to evolve into software companies rather than being strictly machine providers.
[src:iec-62443-security/operational-technology] Security of operational technology systems has historically relied almost entirely on the standalone nature of OT installations, security by obscurity.
[src:iec-62443-security/operational-technology] At least since 2005 OT systems have become linked to IT systems with the corporate goal of widening an organization's ability to monitor and adjust its OT systems, which has introduced massive challenges in securing them.
[src:iec-62443-security/operational-technology] Approaches known from regular IT are usually replaced or redesigned to align with the OT environment.
[src:iec-62443-security/operational-technology] The intersection of operational technology and standard networking infrastructure exposes industrial processes to several distinct categories of risk.
[src:iec-62443-security/operational-technology] Mitigation of these integrated risks typically involves the adoption of multi-layered security frameworks, continuous anomaly monitoring, and adherence to established institutional standards such as the ISA/IEC 62443 series.
[src:iec-62443-security/operational-technology] Operational technology is widely used in refineries, power plants, nuclear plants, etc. and as such has become a common, crucial element of critical infrastructure systems.
[src:iec-62443-security/operational-technology] Depending on the country, critical infrastructure operators may face increasing legal obligations with regard to the implementation of OT systems.
[src:iec-62443-security/operational-technology] For several decades, hundreds of thousands of buildings have been upgraded with IoT building management, automation and smart lighting control solutions, but many of these solutions lack the proper security measures.
[src:iec-62443-security/operational-technology] This has recently led to bad actors exploiting such solutions' vulnerabilities with ransomware attacks causing system lock outs, operational failures exposing businesses operating in such buildings to the immense risks to health and safety, operations, brand reputation and financial damage.
[src:iec-62443-security/operational-technology] There is a strong focus put on subjects like IT/OT cooperation or IT/OT alignment in the modern industrial setting.
[src:iec-62443-security/operational-technology] The Stuxnet malware is one example of this, highlighting the potential for disaster should a safety system become infected with malware (whether targeted at that system or accidentally infected).
[src:iec-62443-security/security-level] In cryptography, **security level** is a measure of the strength that a cryptographic primitive — such as a cipher or hash function — achieves.
[src:iec-62443-security/security-level] Security level is usually expressed as a number of "bits of security" (also **security strength**), where *n*-bit security means that the attacker would have to perform 2*n* operations to break it, but other methods have been proposed that more closely model the costs for an attacker.
[src:iec-62443-security/security-level] This allows for convenient comparison between algorithms and is useful when combining multiple primitives in a hybrid cryptosystem, so there is no clear weakest link.
[src:iec-62443-security/security-level] For example, AES-128 (key size 128 bits) is designed to offer a 128-bit security level, which is considered roughly equivalent to a RSA using 3072-bit key.
[src:iec-62443-security/security-level] In this context, **security claim** or **target security level** is the security level that a primitive was initially designed to achieve, although "security level" is also sometimes used in those contexts.
[src:iec-62443-security/security-level] When attacks are found that have lower cost than the security claim, the primitive is considered **broken**.
[src:iec-62443-security/security-level] Symmetric algorithms usually have a strictly defined security claim.
[src:iec-62443-security/security-level] For symmetric ciphers, it is typically equal to the key size of the cipher — equivalent to the complexity of a brute-force attack.
[src:iec-62443-security/security-level] Cryptographic hash functions with output size of *n* bits usually have a collision resistance security level *n*/2 and a preimage resistance level *n*.
[src:iec-62443-security/security-level] This is because the general birthday attack can always find collisions in 2*n/2* steps.
[src:iec-62443-security/security-level] For example, SHA-256 offers 128-bit collision resistance and 256-bit preimage resistance.
[src:iec-62443-security/security-level] However, there are some exceptions to this.
[src:iec-62443-security/security-level] The Phelix and Helix are 256-bit ciphers offering a 128-bit security level.
[src:iec-62443-security/security-level] The SHAKE variants of SHA-3 are also different: for a 256-bit output size, SHAKE-128 provides 128-bit security level for both collision and preimage resistance.
[src:iec-62443-security/security-level] The design of most asymmetric algorithms (i.e. public-key cryptography) relies on neat mathematical problems that are efficient to compute in one direction, but inefficient to reverse by the attacker.
[src:iec-62443-security/security-level] However, attacks against current public-key systems are always faster than brute-force search of the key space.
[src:iec-62443-security/security-level] Their security level isn't set at design time, but represents a computational hardness assumption, which is adjusted to match the best currently known attack.
[src:iec-62443-security/security-level] Various recommendations have been published that estimate the security level of asymmetric algorithms, which differ slightly due to different methodologies.
[src:iec-62443-security/security-level] The following table are examples of typical security levels for types of algorithms as found in s5.6.1.1 of the US NIST SP-800-57 Recommendation for Key Management.
[src:iec-62443-security/security-level] Under NIST recommendation, a key of a given security level should only be transported under protection using an algorithm of equivalent or higher security level.
[src:iec-62443-security/security-level] The security level is given for the cost of breaking one target, not the amortized cost for group of targets.
[src:iec-62443-security/security-level] It takes 2128 operations to find a AES-128 key, yet the same number of amortized operations is required for any number *m* of keys.
[src:iec-62443-security/security-level] On the other hand, breaking *m* ECC keys using the rho method require sqrt(*m*) times the base cost.
[src:iec-62443-security/security-level] A cryptographic primitive is considered broken when an attack is found to have less than its advertised level of security.
[src:iec-62443-security/security-level] However, not all such attacks are practical: most currently demonstrated attacks take fewer than 240 operations, which translates to a few hours on an average PC.
[src:iec-62443-security/security-level] The costliest demonstrated attack on hash functions is the 261.2 attack on SHA-1, which took 2 months on 900 GTX 1060 GPUs, and cost US$75,000 (although the researchers estimate only $11,000 was needed to find a collision).
[src:iec-62443-security/security-level] Aumasson draws the line between practical and impractical attacks at 280 operations.
[src:iec-62443-security/security-level] The field of post-quantum cryptography considers the security level of cryptographic algorithms in the face of a hypothetical attacker possessing a quantum computer.
[src:iec-62443-security/security-level] Even though quantum computers capable of these operations have yet to appear, adversaries of today may choose to "harvest now, decrypt later": to store intercepted ciphertexts so that they can be decrypted when sufficiently powerful quantum computers become available.
[src:iec-62443-security/security-level] As a result, governments and businesses have already begun work on moving to quantum-resistant algorithms.
[src:iec-62443-security/security-level] Examples of these effort include Google and Cloudflare's tests of hybrid post-quantum TLS on the Internet and NSA's release of Commercial National Security Algorithm Suite 2.0 in 2022.
